     705           1 : //             is a little tricky (see docs right below). The reason is that it is optimized

     715           1 : //         ignored.

    1268           1 : function unSign(value, bits, ignore) {
    1269           1 :   if (value >= 0) {
    1270           1 :     return value;
    1271           1 :   }

    1274           1 : }
    1275           4 : function reSign(value, bits, ignore) {
    1276           4 :   if (value <= 0) {
    1277           4 :     return value;
    1278           4 :   }
    1279           4 :   var half = bits <= 32 ? Math.abs(1 << (bits-1)) // abs is needed if bits == 32
    1280           4 :                         : Math.pow(2, bits-1);
    1281           4 :   if (value >= half && (bits <= 32 || value > half)) { // for huge values, we can hit the precision limit and always get true here. so don't do that
    1282           4 :                                                        // but, in general there is no perfect solution here. With 64-bit ints, we get rounding and errors
    1283           4 :                                                        // TODO: In i64 mode 1, resign the two parts separately and safely
    1284           4 :     value = -2*half + value; // Cannot bitshift half, as it may be at the limit of the bits JS uses in bitshifts
    1285           4 :   }
    1286           4 :   return value;
    1287           4 : }
